s, political experiments, surveys and one-on-one interviews, Scherer illuminates the complicated relationship between diversity and court legitimacy. She shows us how diverse representation can positively impact perceptions of the court among women and racial minorities, while having a negative impact on the perceptions among white people and men. Ultimately, Diversifying the Courts provides insight into the impact of gender, race, and ethnicity on the courts, illuminating some of the major challenges facing the American judicial system in the years that lie ahead.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLAW / Government / General.2bisacsh  aBlack Judicial Appointments.  aBlack judges.  aCourt Appointments.  aCourt Diversity.  aDescriptive Race Representation.  aDescriptive Representation.  aDiversification Strategies.  aDiversity Debate.  aFederal Judges.  aFemale Judicial Appointments.  aGender Representation.  aGovernment Benefits.  aGroup Membership.  aJudicial Appointments.  aJudicial Decision-Making.  aJudicial Diversity.  aJudicial Legitimacy.  aMarginalized Groups.  aParty Identification.  aPerceptions of Legitimacy.  aPolitical Legitimacy.  aPublic Opinion.  aRacial Diversity.  aRacial Representation.  aRacial and Gender Diversity.  aRepresentational Politics.  aSubstantive Representation.  aWhite judges.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023 Englishz978311131929208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2023z9783111318912oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2023 Englishz978311131914808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Law 2023z9783111318226oZDB-23-DGC08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University